@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "The Client in Web Communication";
}

<body data-topic="web-communication-client">
<div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center">What is a Client in Web Communication?</h1>

    <div class="beginner-note">
        <div class="beginner-note-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-laptop"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="beginner-note-content">
            <h4>Think of the Client Like a Customer in a Restaurant</h4>
            <p><strong>Client = Customer</strong> who makes requests (orders food)</p>
            <p><strong>Simple analogy:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>You (Client) go to a restaurant</li>
                <li>You request food from the menu</li>
                <li>You wait for the food to be prepared</li>
                <li>You receive and consume the food</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>In web terms:</strong> The client requests web pages/data, waits for the server to prepare it, then displays it!</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="intro-section">
        <p>A <strong>client</strong> is any device or software application that requests and uses services from a server. When you browse the internet, <strong>you are the client!</strong></p>
        
        <div class="alert alert-info">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Quick Definition:</strong> A client is <strong>ANYTHING that asks for information</strong> from the internet.
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Everyday Examples of Clients</h2>
    
    <div class="examples-section">
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-window-maximize"></i> Web Browsers</h4>
            <p><strong>Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge</strong> - These are the most common clients you use every day!</p>
            <p>When you type "google.com" and press Enter, your browser (client) asks Google's servers for the webpage.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-mobile-alt"></i> Mobile Apps</h4>
            <p><strong>Instagram, Facebook, WhatsApp</strong> apps on your phone</p>
            <p>When you scroll through your feed, the app (client) requests new posts from Instagram's servers.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-desktop"></i> Desktop Applications</h4>
            <p><strong>Spotify, Slack, Zoom</strong> installed on your computer</p>
            <p>When you play a song on Spotify, the desktop app (client) requests music files from Spotify's servers.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-gamepad"></i> Game Clients</h4>
            <p><strong>Fortnite, Minecraft</strong> game applications</p>
            <p>When you play online, the game (client) constantly communicates with game servers.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">How Clients Work - Simple Step-by-Step</h2>
    
    <div class="visual-section">
        <div class="step-diagram">
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-number">1</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h5>You Make a Request</h5>
                    <p>You type a URL (like facebook.com) or click a link in your browser</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-number">2</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h5>Client Prepares the Request</h5>
                    <p>Your browser prepares a message saying: "Hello server, please give me the Facebook homepage"</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-number">3</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h5>Request is Sent</h5>
                    <p>The request travels through the internet to Facebook's servers</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-number">4</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h5>Client Waits for Response</h5>
                    <p>Your browser shows a loading spinner while waiting</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-number">5</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h5>Client Receives & Displays</h5>
                    <p>When the response arrives, your browser displays the Facebook page</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Client Types - Quick Comparison</h2>
    
    <div class="comparison-table">
        <table class="table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type of Client</th>
                    <th>Examples</th>
                    <th>What It Does</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Thin Client</strong></td>
                    <td>Web Browsers</td>
                    <td>Most work is done by the server. Just displays information.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Thick Client</strong></td>
                    <td>Desktop Apps (Photoshop)</td>
                    <td>Does more processing locally, less dependent on server.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Mobile Client</strong></td>
                    <td>Phone Apps (Instagram)</td>
                    <td>Runs on phones/tablets, often works offline too.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Smart Client</strong></td>
                    <td>Progressive Web Apps</td>
                    <td>Works like a website but can save data for offline use.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Real Example: What Your Browser Actually Sends</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-http">
GET /homepage HTTP/1.1
Host: www.facebook.com
User-Agent: Chrome/Windows
Accept: text/html,application/json
Accept-Language: en-US
Connection: keep-alive

(Blank line - request ends here)
</code></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="code-explanation">
            <p><strong>This is what happens when you visit Facebook:</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li><code>GET /homepage</code> = "Please give me the homepage"</li>
                <li><code>Host: www.facebook.com</code> = "I want it from Facebook"</li>
                <li><code>User-Agent: Chrome/Windows</code> = "I'm using Chrome on Windows"</li>
                <li>The empty line at the end means: "That's all I have to say!"</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="interactive-example">
        <h3><i class="fas fa-hand-pointer"></i> Try It Yourself: Be the Client!</h3>
        <div class="interactive-content">
            <p>Imagine you're a web browser. What would you ask for in these situations?</p>
            
            <div class="scenario">
                <p><strong>Scenario 1:</strong> You want to watch a YouTube video about cats.</p>
                <div class="options">
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="true">Ask YouTube: "Please send me the cat video page"</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Ask Google: "What's the weather today?"</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Tell YouTube: "Here's my bank account info"</button>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="scenario">
                <p><strong>Scenario 2:</strong> You're checking your email in Gmail.</p>
                <div class="options">
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Ask Facebook: "Show me my friends"</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="true">Ask Gmail: "Please show me my new emails"</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Tell Gmail: "Play music for me"</button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-points">
        <h3>Key Points to Remember</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Client = Request Maker</strong> - Anything that asks for data from the internet</li>
            <li><strong>You are a client</strong> every time you use the internet</li>
            <li><strong>Different types:</strong> Browsers, mobile apps, desktop apps, games</li>
            <li><strong>Always initiates:</strong> The client always starts the conversation</li>
            <li><strong>Sends requests:</strong> "Please give me this webpage/video/data"</li>
            <li><strong>Receives responses:</strong> Gets back what it asked for (or an error)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("Introduction", "WebCommunication")" class="btn btn-outline-primary ajax-link">← Introduction</a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("Server", "WebCommunication")" class="btn btn-primary ajax-link">Next: What is a Server? →</a>
    </div>
</div>

